Rating: 3
The rating here is for the way the finished product tasted, but the recipe sort of sets you up for failure. Do take the last reviewer's advice and use the two-stage method which you can find in Cook's Illustrated's Baking book or their best recipes books. I got a very moist, golden cake with a nice crumb that DID harden a bit on refridgeration but still had good flavor. The whipped cream icing was the problem -I wanted the berries-and-cream flavor and texture that buttercream couldn't deliver, but whipped cream without stabilizer would not hold the basket weave detail. Find a way to stabilize your cream (corn starch method described by a previous reviewer, gelatin, Dr. Oetker's Whip It, pudding, whatever) or make this in an ice-cold kitchen and/or get a professional friend to find you a quart of real 40% butterfat cream. Even rushing it in and out of the fridge and giving the cream time in the freezer every few minutes wasn't enough to keep the icing stiff. But it really does taste lovely - the orange cream and strawberries together were SO good.

Rating: 3
This cake, as made according to the recipe, is a little ordinary (minus the basketweave fanfare) but still good. Made according to the "two-stage method" (see Cook's Illustrated's "Baking Illustrated" book for instructions), it has a better flavor and finer, lighter texture. I also recommend adding two teaspoons of pure orange extract along with the vanilla and orange peel. The trouble with using a whipped cream frosting is that the cake must be refrigerated. Butter cakes (as opposed to Chiffon cakes) get hard in the fridge. A better option is a Swiss, French or Italian buttercream - or a cream cheese based buttercream - which is very easy (is there anyone who doesn't like cream cheese frosting?). The basket design is quite a bit of piecework. Save yourself the time and trouble and just fill with seedless strawberry jam or strawberry butter (from American Spoon Foods) and frost in the normal fashion. Top with a mound of fresh strawberries in the center. It will still be beautiful and taste wonderful. A lovely cake for Easter and summer, when strawberries are at their peak. It can also be done with seedless raspberry jam and fresh raspberries. For the raspberry version, add a bit of Chambord Liqueur or Bonny Doon Framboise to the buttercream.

