Rating: 4
I've made this several times after getting the recipe from a friend who made it and have always gotten rave reviews. I'm making it this weekend for someone who won it at an auction at my son's school. I agree that the chocolate dipped strawberries on top add a nice touch. Last time I stabilized the whipped cream by adapting a recipe from "The Cake Bible" which says it will not water out for up to 24 hours if kept refrigerated. The icing still tasted great, was nice and thick and stayed that way through leftovers the next day. All you need is a little cornstarch with the listed ingredients. Refrigerate mixing bowl and beaters. In a small saucepan, place 6 Tbs. powdered sugar and 1 Tbs. cornstarch and gradually stir in 3/4 cup of the cream. Bring to a boil, stirring constantly, and simmer for just a few seconds (until the liquid is thickened). Scrape into a small bowl and cool to room temperature. Add the 3/4 tsp. vanilla. Beat the remaining 2 1/4 cups cream, 3/4 cup sour cream, 1 1/2 tsp. orange peel, and remaining 1/4 cup plus 2 Tbs. powdered sugar together in chilled bowl just until traces of beater marks begin to show distinctly. Add the cornstarch mixture in a steady stream, beating constantly. Beat just until stiff peaks form when the beater is raised. This is good for the purists who don't want to use pudding in the icing. :)

